3. Renormalization Group flow R(p):

  p=   2: R(p) = 1.4278613
  p=   3: R(p) = 2.5992648
  p=  19: R(p) = 1.1800579
  p= 191: R(p) = 1.0322553
  p5=3993746143633: R(p) = 1.0648437 <-- transition zone

  Theoretical limits:
  For p < p5 (asymptotic): R(p) ~ ln(2 ln p)/ln(p) -> 0 as p grows
  For p > p5 (asymptotic): R(p) ~ 1 + m/(8 ln p) -> 1 as m grows

  At p5 (small-p formula): ln(2 ln p5)/ln(p5) = 0.13995798
  At p5 (large-p formula): 1+m/(8 ln p5)      = 1.0689281
  Actual R(p5)                                  = 1.0648437

4. Phase boundary approximation (Meta AI derivation):

  Approximation: chi(||p*a0||) ~ log10(2 ln p); chi(1/p) ~ log10(p)
  Setting equal: log10(2 ln p) = log10(p)
                 2 ln p = p  => approximate crossing at small p (not useful)

  Better approximation from Meta AI (including the factor-of-2 correction):
  log10(ln p) = ln p / 2.303 - 0.3
  This cannot be solved in closed form; the LHS grows slowly,
  the RHS grows linearly. The approximation holds for ln p ~ 29:
  At p5: ln(p5) = 29.015751
    LHS = log10(ln p5)         = 1.4626338
    RHS = ln(p5)/2.303 - 0.3   = 12.30138
  Note: LHS and RHS are not equal; the formula is an approximation.
  The key numerical agreement: e^29 = 3.9313343e+12 ~ p5 = 3993746143633
  ln(p5)  = 29.015751
  Both ~ 29: this locates the phase boundary to correct order of magnitude.

5. Boundary condition (from Lemma 2):

  m_boundary = floor(8 ln p5 / ln 191)
             = floor(8 x 29.015751 / 5.2522734)
             = floor(44.195339)
             = 44
  m at p5 = 16 < 44: p5 is INSIDE boundary
  m at p6 = 32 < 44: p6 still inside boundary
  p5 is the last prime where Error > 1/ln(p), i.e. self-similarity holds

6. LLM memory requirement at p5:

  chi(1/p5) = 13
  LLM memory to pad 1/p5: 10^13 tokens
  10^13 = 1.0e+13
  This exceeds any finite context window. Experimental crash confirmed.

